To President Biden, President Trump, and current and future members of Congress: If we do not act forcefully against the ICC after their outrageous decision to issue arrest warrants for the duly elected Israeli Prime Minister and former Minister of Defense, we are making a huge mistake, and I fear the United States is next.

Israel is not a member of the ICC nor is the United States. Israel has a very robust legal system and so does the United States. If we do not fight back against the ICC‚Äôs attack on Israel, it is as if we are conceding that they have jurisdiction over the United States.

We cannot let the world believe for a moment that this is a legitimate exercise of jurisdiction by the Court against Israel because to do so means we could be next.

I will be introducing legislation that puts other countries on notice ‚Äì If you aid and abet the ICC after their action against the State of Israel, you can expect consequences from the United States. Any nation that joins with the ICC after this outrage is a partner in a reckless act that tramples the rule of law.

Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson (IL-01) today expressed his strong support for Congressman Sean Casten‚Äôs (IL-06) letter to the leadership of the House Ethics Committee, calling for the immediate release of the committee‚Äôs report on allegations against former Rep. Matt Gaetz. Nearly 100 House Democrats have signed the letter, which urges transparency and accountability in response to serious allegations against Gaetz, particularly as he is under consideration by former President Donald Trump for the role of U.S. Attorney General.

‚ÄúMatt Gaetz‚Äôs actions have raised grave concerns about his fitness for public office, and it is critical that the House Ethics Committee release its findings so that the American people can have full visibility into the investigation,‚Äù said Congressman Jackson. ‚ÄúAs former Rep. Gaetz‚Äôs name is being floated for such a significant and powerful position in a future administration, it is vital that we address these allegations with the seriousness and transparency they deserve. We cannot allow a person with these unanswered questions to ascend to such a high office. I stand with my colleagues in calling for the Ethics Committee to release its report and hold former Rep. Gaetz accountable for his actions.‚Äù

The letter, signed by nearly 100 House Democrats, comes as the confirmation of Matt Gaetz as Attorney General would mark a significant and troubling shift in the nation‚Äôs leadership. The lawmakers are urging the House Ethics Committee to release its report without delay to ensure transparency and to inform the public about the ongoing investigation into Gaetz‚Äôs conduct.
Congressman Jackson joins his colleagues in calling for accountability and transparency, reaffirming the importance of upholding ethical standards in Congress and safeguarding the integrity of the justice system.

üìç Retaining Your Current Address
Residents whose homes were gravely impacted or destroyed may still retain their current address if desired.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1963, President John F. Kennedy was assassinated while traveling through Dallas, Texas, in a motorcade with his wife Jacqueline, Texas Governor John Connally, and his wife. 

As their car passed the Texas School Book Depository, Lee Harvey Oswald allegedly shot Kennedy from the sixth floor, fatally wounding him and injuring Governor Connally. Kennedy was pronounced dead 30 minutes later at Parkland Hospital. Vice President Lyndon Johnson, who was in the motorcade, was sworn in as president aboard Air Force One shortly afterward.

As Oswald was being transferred within the Dallas police headquarters a few days later, nightclub owner Jack Ruby shot and killed him. Ruby claimed he acted out of anger over Kennedy‚Äôs death, but he was charged with first-degree murder.

James Peebles is a Winterville resident and a dedicated community leader. With over 35 years of service to our nation, James‚Äô dedication and commitment remain unwavering.

He is an enthusiastic volunteer who loves participating in ‚ÄúRead Across America,‚Äù where he inspires young readers in Northampton County through engaging role-playing and valuable life lessons. He also enjoys gardening and shares his produce with seniors and others in need. Additionally, James has coached youth football and basketball, emphasizing teamwork and mentorship, which positively shapes young lives. He is the author of the award-winning book ‚ÄúThe J.O.U.R.N.E.Y.: How to Follow God‚Äôs Will for Your Life,‚Äù which has received Global Ebook awards.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share the remarkable stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals who rise above and inspire us all. Today, we pause to honor the life of an extraordinary man‚ÄîFrank Mongiello of Yardley, an ALS Warrior whom we sadly lost this week, and whose courage, advocacy, and unwavering determination changed lives and inspired a movement of hope.
 
In 2015, Frank's life was forever changed by his ALS diagnosis‚Äîa moment that could have silenced hope for many. Though this devastating disease slowly claimed his ability to walk, talk, swallow, and even breathe, it never touched his indomitable spirit. Instead, he turned his battle into a powerful mission. Refusing to let ALS define him, Frank became a tireless voice for the voiceless and a symbol of resilience and hope for millions of families nationwide.
 
Frank was a driving force behind my Trickett Wendler, Frank Mongiello, Jordan McLinn, & Matthew Bellina Right to Try Act. Our historic law created a new pathway for terminally ill patients caught between the traditional drug approval delays, clinical trials for which they do not qualify, and limited time to access experimental treatments, providing families the opportunity to pursue potentially life-saving treatments for their loved ones. It was one of the greatest honors of my life to work alongside Frank as we fought to turn this vision into a reality. His relentless determination and advocacy were instrumental in shaping this law‚Äîfrom its conception to its passage.
 
Frank was more than an advocate; he was a devoted husband, a proud father of six, and a steadfast friend. Alongside his wife, Marilyn, he used his platform to amplify the voices of others, showing the world the power of courage, compassion, and action. 
 
Frank's story is one of extraordinary strength and selflessness. His unwavering resolve reminds us of the importance of standing up for those who cannot stand for themselves. He showed us that even in the face of unimaginable adversity, hope can ignite change, and determination can move mountains.
 
Please join me in offering condolences to Marilyn, their children, and all who knew and loved Frank‚Äîa true Hometown Hero. While he will be deeply missed, his indomitable spirit will live on and continue to guide us as we fight for a cure in his honor.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1942, Poon Lim, a Chinese steward aboard a British merchant ship, became one of the most famous survivors of a maritime disaster after surviving 133 days at sea when the ship was torpedoed by a German U-boat. 

The ship sank quickly, and Lim was one of the few survivors, managing to escape on a small life raft with little more than some biscuits, a few tins of water, and a flare gun. Stranded in the South Atlantic Ocean, Lim faced extreme challenges, including hunger, dehydration, and brutal exposure to the elements. Using his resourcefulness, he fashioned fishing tools from parts of the raft and caught fish with his bare hands. He also collected rainwater to stay hydrated and used the raft's canopy for shelter from the sun during the day. 

Over the course of his journey, he drifted more than 2,000 miles until he was rescued by a Brazilian fishing boat. By then, he had lost over 40 pounds. Lim was awarded the British Empire Medal for his incredible endurance and determination.

text:
Starting off we have the $6.8 million question:
¬†
What food, toys, scents, and humans do cats enjoy the most?

Bad news: we aren't within a whisker of all the waste.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
$390,000 was dedicated to uncovering the elusive question ‚Äî how many shakes does it take for a wet cat to dry off?

If you had 9, congratulations ‚Äî you are correct!

There is no time to paws and reflect, there is a lot more waste to go.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
You can't forget about the $178,000 "catwalk" study.
¬†
@NIH put 10 cats on a catwalk and another on a treadmill to study how they balance.
¬†
Why tax dollars were spent on this is purrplexing.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Now we arrive at one of the biggest mysteries in the universe, who can urinate faster - a cat or an elephant?

For a cool $331,000, it turns out it is a tie!

18 seconds each for these speed demons.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

It would be hiss-terical if it wasn't funded by your tax dollars.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
Lastly, you may be jealous of whoever got paid by the Navy to study the appeal of cute kittens on the internet.

text:
@NIH is playing some real cat and mouse games with tax dollars, creating glow in the dark cats and mice.

Hard to understand the purr-pose of this.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1986, it is revealed that the United States had been secretly selling weapons to Iran and giving the funds to the Contras, an anti-communist group in Nicaragua, known as the Iran-Contra Affair. 

The original arms deal, first reported in early November, was meant to secure the release of seven American hostages in Lebanon but violated U.S. policies, including the arms embargo against Iran and President Reagan‚Äôs pledge not to negotiate with terrorists. A few weeks later, it was disclosed that the funds from these sales were used to support the Contras, which directly violated the 1982 Boland Amendment prohibiting U.S. aid for overthrowing Nicaragua's government.

In the wake of this revelation, President Reagan accepted responsibility for the arms-for-hostages deal but denied knowledge of the funds diversion. A special prosecutor was appointed to investigate, and televised hearings followed, finding that officials attempted to cover up their illegal actions. They concluded that while Reagan and Vice President George Bush didn‚Äôt break the law, their actions contributed to a broader effort to deceive Congress and the public.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
üßµWe can eliminate more than $2 trillion of waste in Washington in 22 easy steps.
¬†
Here is how @elonmusk, @VivekGRamaswamy, and @DOGE can begin to trim the fat and #makeemsqueal. üëá

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
1. Ghost Workers üëª
¬†
We are spending $15.7 billion a year on underutilized buildings.

Many are vacant!

Bureaucrats refuse to show up to work, so why are we paying for empty buildings?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
2. Audit the IRS
¬†
Hundreds of IRS agents owe millions in back taxes. 

150,000 federal employees owe $1.5 billion in back taxes government-wide.

After we are done, these numbers need to be zero.

Name: Ernst, Joni
Ernst, Joni
text:
3. Undo Biden's Billion-Dollar Boondoggles
¬†
Biden has spent $7.5 billion to build 17 EV charging stations and $42 billion to expand rural broadband but has connected zero people to the internet.

Pulling the plug on these programs will be the only efficient part about them.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
4. Cancel the Crazy California Gravy Trains üöÇ 
¬†
Three trains in California are costing taxpayers $144 billion to build.

Let's put a stop to these train wrecks.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
6. End Welfare for Politicians
¬†
The Presidential Election Campaign Fund uses tax dollars to fund the candidacy of longshot and fringe candidates running for the White House.

Tax dollars shouldn‚Äôt be financing the failed ambitions of politicians ‚Äì let's save $16.6 million.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
8. Trillion Dollar Secret Slush Funds
¬†
Washington is hiding $1.6 trillion in unobligated funds, including billions from COVID.
¬†
We should not be hording money for secret pet projects when we are $36 trillion in debt.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
7. Bad Pennies

Currently, the federal government is paying 3 cents to produce a penny and 11 cents to make a nickel.

That makes no sense!

Only Washington could lose money making money.

Changing the composition of coins would save $50 million a year.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
10. Silly Science ¬†

ü¶êHow fast does a shrimp run on a treadmill?

üêºHow fast does a panda poop?

üöΩWhich tastes better - toilet water or bottled water?

üêòCan elephants solve puzzles?

These are just a few of the bizarre studies funded using hundreds of millions in tax dollars.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
9. Bogus Bonuses üöÄüõ∞Ô∏è

The federal government spends hundreds of millions of dollars giving bureaucrats and contractors unearned bonuses for work that often never took place, including more than $500 million at @NASA.

Time to end this moondoggle.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
11. Unemployment for Millionaires

Nearly 15,000 Americans earning a million dollars in income collected $213 million in unemployment last year.

The million-dollar question - why are hardworking folks paying for this?

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
12. Government Swag
¬†
Federal agencies collectively spend $1.5 billion every year on public relations including snuggies, mascots, key chains, and coloring books.

Let's bag the swag.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
13. Head in the Clouds ‚òÅÔ∏èüíª
¬†
Consolidating federal agencies‚Äô cloud computing software licenses would save $750 million a year.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
14. China's Mad Scientists¬†üßë‚Äçüî¨

My investigations uncovered that Dr. Fauci and others have sent millions to shady Chinese labs for sketchy experiments.

The worst part is that a lack of transparency means we don't even know how many millions are being spent or for what.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
16. Defenseless Spending

The Pentagon wastes $125 billion on bloated bureaucracy and has never passed an audit.

Let's declare war on wasteful spending.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
15. UN Overpayments
¬†
The USA pays higher dues to the UN than any other country, and sends $15 billion more voluntarily, despite UN employees participating in terrorist attacks and encouraging illegal immigration to the USA.

Why are tax dollars undermining our national security?

Federal employees with no work assignments admit to napping, playing dominoes, and chess on the clock.

Name: Ernst, Joni

Name: Ernst, Joni

20. Snap Back Payments ü´∞

Name: Ernst, Joni

22. Common Sense

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text:
I joined the governor, the mayor, and state & local officials in announcing that, at long last, Newtonville will be getting a new commuter rail station. Commuters can look forward to an accessible, comfortable station that improves the reliability of their commute. And all of Newtonville can count on improved transit infrastructure to support walkable housing development.

This upgrade is bigger than just Newtonville, though: it also removes one of the bottlenecks to the ultimate implementation of both West-East rail and regional rail. The new station will be an unlock for the system.

At a time when remote work and other new, post-COVID patterns of life are challenging the MBTA, all levels of government must work together to invest in a system that reliably connects people to jobs, services, and each other; that supports housing production; and that builds public trust in governance. This project is an example of that partnership, and I‚Äôm gratified to have been one part of it through congressionally directed spending and through partnership with MBTA General Manager Phil Eng.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1789, the first national Thanksgiving in America takes place. 

The "first" Thanksgiving was held by the Pilgrims in 1621 at Plymouth, where they feasted to thank God for their harvest, inviting the Wampanoag tribe to join them. While this event was not repeated annually, similar observances occurred in other colonies and to celebrate victories in battle. In 1789, President George Washington proclaimed November 26 as a national day of thanksgiving to celebrate the creation of the United States and its new Constitution. Washington personally marked the day by attending church services and making charitable donations.

However, Washington‚Äôs proclamation did not establish Thanksgiving as a permanent federal holiday. Although other presidents, like John Adams and James Madison, issued thanksgiving proclamations, it did not become an annual observance until Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs presidency during the Civil War.

Name: Lee, Mike
text:
I am proud to introduce S.5364, the App Store Accountability Act, to keep kids safe from exploitation online.

Too many companies profit from adult content reaching children, and it‚Äôs going to stop. 

First, this bill creates a private right of action for parents and guardians against app stores that expose their children to pornographic content and extreme violence. 

That means these companies can be sued. 

App stores can protect themselves from liability by enforcing age verification and parental controls. 

We have the technology to ensure age-verification without ending anonymity online or endangering First Amendment rights, and we should use it. 
 
Younger and younger children are seeing sexual and violent content online through a variety of apps. 

If we want to stop this vicious trend, we can‚Äôt rely on big corporations to be ‚Äúmoral.‚Äù 

We need them to know they‚Äôll go bankrupt if they victimize kids. 

The App Store Accountability Act tells them.
